flowRoot.flowPara: Gravitational fields in spherical coordinates using Tesseroids with variable density
Santiago R. Soler1,2, Agustina Pesce1,2, Mario E. Gimenez1,2 and Leonardo Uieda3
1 CONICET 2 IGSV, UNSJ 3 Department of Earth Sciences, SOEST, University of Hawai'i at Manoa, USA.

When computing gravitational fileds on regional or global scales it's necessary to take into account the curvature of the Earth. One way to do this is using spherical prisms, also known as Tesseroids. Most methodologies consider only Tesseorids with homogeneous density or with specific density variations in depth, like linear or polynomial. We propose a new methodology to compute the gravitational fields generated by Tesseroids with any continuous density variation in depth through GLQ and two discretization algorithms.
The gravitational potential generated by a tesseroid with variable density in depth can be numerically approximated throught a Gauss-Legendre Quadrature (GLQ).
The GLQ is equivalent to approximating the tesseroid with point masses located on the nodes of the Quadrature.
The approximation becomes less accurate when the computation points gets closer to the tesseroid. To reduce this error we use a two dimensional adaptive discretization algorithm.

We have developed a complementary discretization algorithm that takes reduces the errors due to the variations of the density function. In short, it divides the tesseroid along the radial dimension at the depths at which the maximum density variation takes place.

We want to find the optimal values of D and that guarantee accuracy while minimize the computation time. In order to do that we compared the numerical results with the analytical solutions of a spherical shell.
